{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SDWD8W9Rk9cSPyQkzTRCFb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests whether the LLM generates a function with the correct signature. This depends on what the real LLM produces.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - the correctness depends on what the real LLM generates. A stub would always return the same signature, hiding failures.\n- Actually wait - if we're testing whether the service correctly VALIDATES the signature, that's different from whether the LLM generates the right signature. \n- If we're testing that the service checks/enforces the signature matches, that's Integration (parsing logic).\n\n\n- If we're testing that the LLM actually generates the correct signature, that's Agentic. The behavior is about what the LLM produces, not the validation logic, so this is Agentic.\n\n**Behavior 2**: Orchestration executes attempts in order and returns immediately on the first passing attempt.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is really about the control flow and early-exit logic of the orchestration module. I can stub both the LLM and test runner to verify the ordering and whether it stops on the first success, so this is Integration level. It doesn't depend on real LLM output quality or infrastructure.\n\nFor Behavior 3, I need actual LLM calls since the whole point is testing that the iterative loop can recover from initial failures through multiple refinement attempts—this is a Workflow-level test that requires real agentic steps.\n\nBehavior 4 is about the deterministic logic of how the prompt builder constructs the next prompt with failed test names and messages, so I'm checking whether that function correctly assembles the refinement prompt.\n\nBehavior 5 tests whether the LLM actually produces different implementation content based on the failure context it receives, which requires real LLM calls to verify the behavior changes meaningfully. changes its output when given failure context. This requires a real LLM call to verify that the model responds differently to the refined prompt.\n- A stub would always return the same thing regardless, hiding the failure.\n- MULTI-STEP: We need at least two steps: first attempt (fail) → second attempt (different code). This involves multiple agentic steps.\n- Minimum level: Agentic (or Workflow since it involves sequential steps)\n- Actually, the behavior says \"live attempt changes implementation content\" - this requires real LLM calls to verify the behavior. It requires at minimum: generate (fail) → refine prompt → generate again. That's multiple agentic steps in sequence → Workflow.\n- But could it be just Agentic? Agentic is \"result depends on real LLM non-determinism or real AI/ML model call\". The key question is whether the second response differs from the first, which only real LLM calls in sequence can verify → Workflow.\n\nFor behavior 6, the service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results. This is orchestration logic around control flow and result packaging, not dependent on real LLM calls since we can stub the code generation to always fail. This feels like an Integration test since it's testing how the loop, test runner, and result packaging work together.\n\nBehavior 7 involves wiring up the full non-agentic pipeline with the generate call, test execution, and attempt tracking. that's Integration. The \"non-agentic pipeline wiring\" language points to everything being mocked out, so Integration is the right level.\n\nFor Behavior 8, this is clearly Workflow—it's a full live loop with real LLM calls running multiple agentic steps in sequence (generate, test, refine, retest) to solve a genuinely hard problem that fails on the first try.\n\nNow I'm compiling all the assessments across the eight behaviors to determine the overall minimum level. Behavior 1 is definitely agentic—the real test is whether the LLM generates a matching signature, not whether a parser can extract it. Behavior 4 is unit-level since it's just checking the prompt construction function with test failure data as input. Behavior 5 requires actual LLM calls to verify the implementation changes in response to failure context, so that's agentic too. and 3 are the real agentic steps that matter—the actual LLM calls with different contexts. Steps 4 and 5 are just verification. So this is definitely Workflow since it requires sequential agentic execution to test whether the implementation actually changes based on failure feedback.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the test classifications and what each one needs to verify. For the Agentic test, I'm checking that a real LLM call produces a function with the right signature. The Integration test stubs the LLM and verifies it exits early on success. The Workflow tests run the full loop—one verifies we find a passing implementation within attempts, another checks that failure context gets properly incorporated into the refinement prompt. The Unit test is straightforward: feed a test failure to the prompt builder and verify the output includes the test details.\n\nFor the remaining Integration tests, one stubs the LLM to always fail and confirms we stop at the attempt limit with a structured error response, while another uses deterministic LLM outputs to verify the entire pipeline wiring works correctly. The final Workflow test runs against a genuinely difficult function with a real LLM to confirm we can solve it within the attempt budget.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence scores for each test level. The signature match test has high confidence as Agentic since it depends on real LLM output quality, but could also work at Integration or Unit levels with lower probability.\n\nFor orchestration early exit, it's most likely an Integration test since it coordinates multiple components, though it could be a single Unit-level function. The live iterative loop is primarily a Workflow concern with multiple sequential steps, though it might appear in Agentic testing with a single LLM call. The refinement prompt test is strongest at the Unit level where I can test the prompt builder logic directly, with some Integration possibility if the test runner is involved.\n\nNext, testing whether live attempts change content would be Agentic-focused with a single pair of LLM calls, but really belongs in Workflow testing since it involves sequential steps. The stopping condition after 3 failures needs Integration testing to wire the loop counter with the test runner and result packaging. Finally, I'm looking at how the non-agentic pipeline components connect together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10002,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10002},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"141cd211-bcb8-4445-8fbd-dae00d671ca5","uuid":"a75bdcf1-6175-4e18-8000-76bea0460cfa"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SDWD8W9Rk9cSPyQkzTRCFb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FQDxK2mpArg84BLJEvM8op","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode here is that the real LLM generates a signature that deviates from the expected interface. LLM-DEP: Correctness depends entirely on what the real LLM produces — a stubbed LLM always returns the same canned code and will always pass or always fail, hiding whether the actual model honors the interface spec. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network primitives needed beyond the LLM API call. MULTI-STEP: A single LLM generation call suffices; no chained agentic steps required. REJECTION-GATE: Integration is disqualified because a stub replaces the model's judgment with a constant — any divergence in how the real LLM interprets the description's interface spec is invisible. The behavior is specifically about what the LLM generates, not about parsing or routing logic around it.","test_description":"Submit a natural language description with a precisely specified interface (e.g., `def compute(a: int, b: int) -> float`) to the real LLM-backed generation endpoint. Extract the generated function's signature and assert that parameter names, types, and return type exactly match the spec. Run multiple times to detect nondeterministic deviations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Orchestration executes attempts in order and returns immediately on the first passing attempt.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the orchestration control flow — does the loop actually stop early when tests pass, rather than continuing unnecessarily? This only manifests when the orchestrator, stub LLM, and stub test runner are wired together so you can observe attempt count and return timing. LLM-DEP: No — the LLM can be stubbed; the behavior under test is the control flow, not model output quality. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network primitives required. MULTI-STEP: Multiple LLM calls occur but they are all stubbed. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network. (b) No real LLM needed. (c) No chained real agentic steps. Wiring the orchestrator with a stub LLM and stub test runner at the module boundary is sufficient to observe whether early exit fires correctly.","test_description":"Wire the orchestrator with a stub LLM that returns passing code on attempt 2 and a stub test runner that returns failure for attempt 1 and success for attempt 2. Assert the orchestrator returns the attempt-2 result, records exactly 2 attempts, and does not invoke the LLM a third time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For a function that a single call usually fails, the live iterative loop can still produce a passing implementation within the allowed attempts.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Usually fails' is a probabilistic statement about the real LLM's first-pass quality — a stub cannot model this. MULTI-STEP: Verifying the iterative loop requires running the full generate→test→refine→generate→test sequence with a real LLM, which is multiple real agentic steps chained in order. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic (single step) is disqualified because the claim is specifically about the iterative loop converging across attempts — a single LLM call cannot test whether the chained refinement process recovers from an initial failure.","test_description":"Provide a known target function that the real LLM reliably fails on the first attempt (e.g., a tricky algorithmic problem). Run the full live iterative pipeline against a real test suite. Assert that within 3 attempts, a passing implementation is produced and the service returns a success result. Track attempt count to confirm the loop advanced past attempt 1.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.75}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When tests fail, the refinement prompt builder includes the failed test names and failure messages in the next LLM prompt.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is purely in the prompt construction function — does it embed the right fields from the test result object into the output string? This is algorithmic/formatting logic isolated to one function. LLM-DEP: No real LLM is needed; we only need to inspect the prompt text the builder produces. REAL-INFRA: No OS or network. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a-d) all no. The function takes structured test-failure data as input and returns a string; its correctness is fully observable at the unit boundary. REJECTION-GATE: Integration would be needed only if the test result data must pass through a module handoff to reach the builder, but the behavior targets the builder's own logic, not module wiring.","test_description":"Construct a deterministic test-failure payload (test name, failure message, traceback) using model classes. Call the refinement prompt builder directly with that payload. Assert the returned prompt string contains the exact test name and failure message as substrings, and that each failed test is represented.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The next live attempt changes implementation content in response to prior failure context rather than resubmitting the same code.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"LLM-DEP: Whether the real LLM actually changes its output when given failure context is a question about model behavior — a stub always returns a constant, making this comparison meaningless with fakes. MULTI-STEP: Verifying the change requires running the full sequence: real LLM call 1 → test runner → real LLM call 2 with enriched prompt. Two sequential real agentic calls are required. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic (single step) is disqualified because the behavior is specifically comparative across two sequential model calls — you cannot observe 'changed in response to context' without running both calls in pipeline order. Integration is disqualified because a stubbed LLM always returns the same code regardless of the prompt, so the assertion would trivially fail or trivially pass.","test_description":"Run the full live pipeline on a function where the first attempt reliably fails tests. Capture the generated code from attempt 1. Let the pipeline proceed to attempt 2 using the real LLM with the failure-enriched prompt. Assert that the source code in attempt 2 differs from attempt 1 (e.g., different function body, different algorithm), confirming the model responded to failure context rather than echoing prior output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.22,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode involves the orchestrator's loop counter, the handoff of per-attempt results to the error builder, and the final structured error shape — this requires wiring those modules together with a stub LLM that always returns failing code. A single unit test on the loop counter alone would not catch missing attempt data in the error payload. LLM-DEP: No real LLM required; stub the LLM to always return syntactically valid but behaviorally failing code. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a-d) all no. REJECTION-GATE: System and Agentic are disqualified because the behavior's correctness depends on module state handoff (accumulating attempt records), not real infrastructure or real model output quality.","test_description":"Wire the orchestrator with a stub LLM that always returns code that fails the test suite, and a stub test runner that always returns failure with distinct test names and messages for each attempt. Invoke the service. Assert it returns a structured error object, that the error contains exactly 3 attempt records, and that each record holds the generated code and the corresponding test failure details.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The full non-agentic pipeline wiring (generate call, test execution, attempt bookkeeping) works end to end with deterministic stubbed model outputs.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior explicitly targets module wiring — whether the generate call, test executor, and bookkeeping components hand data to each other correctly. This only manifests when all three are wired together; unit tests on each component individually would not catch interface mismatches between them. LLM-DEP: The behavior itself says 'deterministic stubbed model outputs', explicitly ruling out real LLM dependency. REAL-INFRA: Test execution could involve a real subprocess, but the behavior scopes to 'non-agentic pipeline wiring' with stubs, so an in-process fake test executor suffices. REJECTION-GATE: System is disqualified by the behavior's own text ('deterministic stubbed model outputs'), which indicates in-process stubs are intended. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified by the same text.","test_description":"Wire all pipeline components (generator, test runner, bookkeeper) using deterministic stubs: the stub LLM returns a fixed valid implementation on call 1 and a different fixed implementation on call 2; the stub test runner returns failure for implementation 1 and success for implementation 2. Invoke the full pipeline and assert: attempt 1 result is recorded with failure details, attempt 2 result is recorded with success, and the service returns the attempt-2 implementation as its final output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The full live loop (generate, test, refine, retest) solves at least one known hard function that fails in the first attempt.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"LLM-DEP: Correctness depends on the real LLM's ability to generate passing code and respond to refinement prompts — stubs replace the model's reasoning with a constant and cannot test whether the real pipeline converges. MULTI-STEP: The full pipeline requires at minimum: real LLM generate → real test execution → real LLM refine → real test execution. Multiple real agentic steps in sequence. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic (single step) is disqualified because the behavior requires the full iterative loop including at least one refinement cycle with a real test failure feeding back into a real LLM call. Integration/System are disqualified because real LLM output quality governs whether the loop converges.","test_description":"Select a curated 'hard' target function known to fail on the LLM's first attempt. Run the full live pipeline end-to-end with the real LLM and a real test suite. Assert that the service returns a passing result within 3 attempts, and that the passing implementation actually passes all tests when executed independently. Log all attempts for debugging non-deterministic